  "prompt": "Nerve cell function?",
  "response": "Nerve cells, or neurons, are specialized cells that play a crucial role in the nervous system by transmitting information throughout the body. They have unique structures and functions that enable them to carry out their roles effectively. Here are the key aspects of nerve cell function:\n\n1. **Transmission of Electrical Signals**: Neurons transmit signals through electrical impulses called action potentials. When a neuron receives a stimulus, a change in membrane potential occurs, leading to the generation of an action potential that travels along the axon toward other neurons or target tissues.\n\n2. **Communication**: Neurons communicate with each other and with other types of cells through synapses. When an action potential reaches the end of a neuron (axon terminal), it triggers the release of neurotransmitters\u2014chemical messengers that cross the synaptic gap and bind to receptors on the adjacent neuron or target cell.\n\n3. **Integration of Information**: Neurons receive inputs from other neurons through their dendrites and cell body. They integrate these signals, determining whether to generate an action potential based on the cumulative strength and timing of incoming signals.\n\n4. **Types of Neurons**: There are several types of neurons based on their function:\n   - **Sensory Neurons**: Transmit sensory information from receptors to the central nervous system (CNS).\n   - **Motor Neurons**: Convey commands from the CNS to effectors (muscles and glands).\n   - **Interneurons**: Facilitate communication between sensory and motor neurons and play a role in reflexes and complex processes.\n\n5. **Plasticity**: Neurons exhibit neuroplasticity, meaning they can strengthen or weaken connections based on activity and experience. This adaptability is essential for learning and memory.\n\n6. **Supporting Cells**: While neurons are the primary signaling cells, they are supported by glial cells (such as astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, and Schwann cells) that provide structural support, maintain homeostasis, form myelin sheaths, and assist in signal transmission.\n\nIn summary, nerve cells are fundamental to receiving, processing, and transmitting information throughout the body, enabling everything from reflexes to complex cognitive functions.",
